post_text:
School Board seeks applicants for open Director position

The Castle Rock School Board of Directors is seeking applicants to fill the unexpired At Large term of Andy Ogden who will resign on September 30, 2020, after 6 years of service to the district.

Director Ogden was scheduled to serve through November of 2021. The Board of Directors will accept applications for the position until 3 p.m., Wednesday, September 23, 2020. The Board will meet in an executive session during their September 29th, Board Meeting to review applicant qualifications and will reconvene to an open session for the selection of candidates to interview in open session during the regular meeting on September 29, 2020, starting at 6:00 p.m. The board is expected to appoint a new member on October 1, 2020.

Applications for the position are available at www.crschools.org under the School Board Tab or pick up the documents at Castle Rock School District Office on 600 Huntington Ave. S.

shared_text:
Castle Rock PTO
September 8 at 7:38 PM ·

Home School Supplies Now, Backpacks Later:

Thanks to generous funds raised and matched by Red Canoe, and of course our amazing community of PTO supporters, we've been able to assemble a few take-home school supplies for students in need. The primary and intermediate school offices have these in pencil boxes. Middle school has them stored in the back of the office, and the High School has them in the school counselor's office.

If you supplies, please stop by your school during normal office hours to pick them up. If you need to make arrangements to pick them up outside of office hours, please contact us at castlerockpto@yahoo.com or on our facebook page or call/text Jessica Lakey at (253) 678-1452.

(FYI, Backpacks will be available in school offices when hybrid in-person attendance starts. The supplies you pick up now should be able to stay at home.)

The Castle Rock School Board is looking for applicants....

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:

School Board seeks applicants for open Director position

The Castle Rock School Board of Directors is seeking applicants to fill the unexpired term of David Dangleis who will resign on August 31, 2020, after 4. 5 years of service to the district.

Dangleis was scheduled to serve through November of 2023. The Board of Directors will accept applications for the position until 3 p.m., August 21, 2020. The Board will meet in an executive session during their August 25th regular meeting to review applicant qualifications and will reconvene to an open session for the selection of candidates to interview in open session during a special meeting on September 1, 2020, starting at 5:30 p.m. The board is expected to appoint a new member on September 1, 2020.

Applications for the position will be available on Monday 8/10/20 at www.crschools.org under the School Board Tab or pick up the documents at Castle Rock School District Office on 600 Huntington Ave. S.

post_text:
Attention High School Students:

The yearbooks are here! If you purchased a yearbook, come to the school Tuesday, June 30, 11:00-1:00, to pick yours up! You must wear a mask and maintain 6' social distancing.

If you can't pick up your own yearbook, you may have someone else pick it up for you. They must bring a note from you, giving them permission to pick up your yearbook. The note must include:

The printed name of the person picking up your yearbook (even if the person is a family member)

Your printed name and signature

No exceptions!

If you have not purchased a yearbook yet, there will be a limited quantity available, first come first served.

The next time to pick up yearbooks will be in August, the date and time to be announced later

text:

TDN.COM
Feb. 11 election results: Four of six local school levies pass

post_text:
Levy is Proposition 1 - preliminary Cowlitz results are looking very positive - it just needs 50%+1 to pass.

Bond is Proposition 2 and needs 60%+1, so it is not looking likely to pass based on these preliminary Cowlitz results.

(As far as we know these numbers do not include Lewis county's votes.)

Overall we are very encouraged by the high voter turnout - looks like the best in the county!

Our thanks to everyone that supported our teachers and staff and the quality of education we can offer through the Levy. Seriously, it makes every difference in the everyday experience of our students.

Looks like we need to go back to the drawing board for a way to get our buildings in the same condition to meet the needs of our students.

We appreciate every effort our community has made during this last few months and hope we can all put in the same efforts and even more in the next campaign as we pursue solutions for Castle Rock Schools. Thank you for your support ❤️ and voting...

post_text:
Do you know the difference between a levy and a bond?

The levy funds things and staff members that the state doesn’t cover. The money from the state only pays for 3 teachers per grade level at the Primary School. That means we would go down from 5 teachers per grade level to 3, causing class sizes to go up to an average of 36 students per class. The levy also pays for paraprofessionals’ counselors, custodians, and so much more.

The bond would pay for building expenses, building upgrades, security and technology around the district.

Please remember to vote! #rocksolid

A Message from our High School Principal.

Dear Parents and Guardians,
We are serious about our students' safety at Castle Rock High School. As a principal, I wanted to make you aware of a situation that occurred today. Administration received a tip that a student may have a weapon in a vehicle on school property. We moved quickly to investigate and during our search we did find that a student had a firearm in the student's vehicle. At no time was there any immediate danger to students or staff. The police are investigating this matter.

The Quarterback Club is doing a fundraiser!

The QB Club does great things for the FB team with the most recent being some helmets and a new high end video system for recording. They are selling select seats in the stadium for $75 this includes a season pass as well. Good for all middle school and high school home football games. They are also selling reserved front row parking spots for $100. Please reach out to Jared Curtiss to reserve. Also if you are interested in becoming a member of the QB Club please reach out to Coach Kyle Godinho. This give you chance to have an app to review games on your own and/or to be part of the tape reviews with some coaches every week. Thanks!

post_text: The past two years, Castle Rock School District has supported it's new teachers through a mentor program. This year, (year two of the mentor program), we expanded our support to professional learning for first, second and third year teachers. Last night was our February workshop and it was a great success. Teachers participated in two different learning sessions facilitated and led by our Instructional Leadership Team (teacher leaders and principals). Mentors supported their mentees as the new teachers learned more about classroom management, student engagement, questioning, teaching writing and the pacing of a lesson. A HUGE THANKS go out to our new teachers, mentors, instructional leadership team and principals for giving up an evening for continued professional learning and growth.

post_text:
**CRHS Situation Update**
Castle Rock High School Administration learned of a possible threat that was posted on Facebook by a student shortly before school began on Friday morning (1/19/18). Castle Rock Police were informed of the possible threat and investigated the matter immediately. The Castle Rock Police Department and school district administration determined there was no threat to the school.

After a thorough investigation, in cooperation with local law enforcement, we are confident there is no existing threat to our students. We are taking extra measures to ensure that a safe environment is provided for our students and staff. Extra police are on site today as a calming measure.

post_text:
DID YOU KNOW...
• Students should miss no more than 9 days of school each year to stay engaged, successful and on track to graduation.
• Absences can be a sign that a student is losing interest in school, struggling with school work, dealing with a peer issue or facing some other potentially serious difficulty.
• By 6th grade, absenteeism is one of three signs that a student may drop out of high school.
• By 9th grade, regular and high attendance is a better predictor of graduation rates than 8th grade test scores.
• Missing 10 percent, or about 18 days, of the school year can drastically affect a student’s academic success.
• Students can be chronically absent even if they only miss a day or two every few weeks.
• Attendance is an important life skill that will help your child graduate from college and keep a job.

post_text: We are happy to announce next year we are beginning AVID! Students in grades 3, 4 and 5 will benefit from AVID strategies throughout their day in their classroom. At the middle school, we are recruiting students who will be in 6th and 7th grade next year to be in our inaugural AVID elective classrooms... Please visit our crschools.org website for the application and turn it in to your school office. We look forward to lots of fun activities, team building, academic support and learning!
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
What Is AVID
text:
We are happy to announce next year we are beginning AVID! Students in grades 3, 4 and 5 will benefit from AVID strategies throughout their day in their classroom. At the middle school, we are recruiting students who will be in 6th and 7th grade next year to be in our inaugural AVID elective classrooms... Please visit our crschools.org website for the application and turn it in to your school office. We look forward to lots of fun activities, team building, academic support and learning!

YOUTUBE.COM
What Is AVID

post_text: Looking for something fun to do over summer break? The Oregon Parks and Recreation Department is pleased to offer a summer series of guided weekend outings for beginning campers of ALL ages. With hands-on lessons, nature hikes and fun family activities, Let’s Go Camping makes camping easy. These events take place all across Oregon and may be coming to a park near you. Check out the dates and locations... Have fun! http://oregonstateparks.org/index.cfm?do=thingstodo.dsp_letsGoCamping
